> Kedgeree is a brilliant example of an Anglo-Indian culinary mash up, having started
> its life as 'khichari', a spiced Indian dish of rice and lentils. Traditionally
> enjoyed for breakfast, chef Mimi decided to give this flavoursome dish her own
> twist, subbing out hard boiled eggs in favour of crunchy stir-fried green beans,
> to make it the perfect dinner time dish. Breakfast for dinner? It's a yes from us!

Boil your kettle. Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1} into roughly 1/2cm pieces.
Mix the boiling @water for the stock{300%ml} with the @vegetable stock pot{1} in a
#measuring jug{}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on medium heat, add the
@onion{1}(halved, peeled and chopped). Cook until soft, stirring occasionally,
~{5%minutes}. Add the @ground turmeric{3/4%tsp} and cook for ~{1%minute} more.
Add the @basmati rice{150%g} and stock. Stir and bring to the boil. Once boiling,
reduce the heat to medium-low, pop a #lid{} on. Cook for ~{10%minutes}, then
remove from the heat and set aside (still covered) for another ~{10%minutes}.

> TIP: The rice will finish cooking in its own steam.

Meanwhile, pour the @water{150%ml} into a #frying pan{}. Place on medium-high heat
and bring to the boil. Lay in the @smoked haddock{2} fillets skin-side up. Cover
the pan with a lid (or some tightly fitting foil), lower the heat to medium-low
and poach the haddock for ~{10%minutes}.

> TIP: The fish is cooked when the centre is opaque.

While the haddock poaches, trim the tops from the @green beans{1}. Discard the
tops and chop the beans into four pieces. Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}
(stalks and all).

When the haddock is cooked, carefully remove it from the #pan{} to a #board{} and
peel off the skin. Discard the skin and cover the haddock with foil (still on your
board) to keep warm. Wash your frying pan and pop back onto medium-high heat and
add a drizzle of @oil{}. Add the beans to the pan along with a pinch of @salt{} and
some @black pepper{}. Stir-fry until slightly browned and softened,
~{4-5%minutes}.

Once the rice is ready, fluff it up with a #fork{} and stir in the haddock
(breaking it into large flakes), the beans, half the parsley and half the
@sour cream{1}. Taste and add @black pepper{} if you feel it needs it. Serve the
kedgeree in #bowls{} with a small spoonful of sour cream on top and the remaining
parsley sprinkled over. Enjoy!